1. How effective was the Russian misinformation campaign described in the M=
ueller indictment?=C2=A0

This question is the most important of the five, and the one least likely t=
o be answered to anyone's satisfaction. But three articles from the Times f=
rame the debate well.=C2=A0

Start with Scott Shane's piece about the unwitting Americans who helped Rus=
sia in its campaign (https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/18/us/politics/russian=
-operatives-facebook-twitter.html). This anecdote captures the absurdity of=
 some of the real-world protests organized in the United States by Russia.

A dozen people who turned out for the first event, some carrying rifles, Co=
nfederate flags and a banner saying =E2=80=9CWhite Lives Matter,=E2=80=9D f=
aced off across a street with a far larger crowd of counterprotesters. The =
police kept the crowds apart, and there was no trouble at the event, which =
was caught on video.Later, on social media, some puzzled participants compl=
ained that no one from Heart of Texas, which had about 250,000 likes on Fac=
ebook, had shown up for the group=E2=80=99s own rally.Now zoom out to this =
higher-level view of the question, from Jonathan Martin and Maggie Haberman=
. It's important to consider Russian activity on Facebook and other platfor=
ms in the context of their larger misinformation war:

The interference was not limited to the actions laid out by Mr. Mueller in =
the indictment of the 13 Russians linked to a =E2=80=9Ctroll farm=E2=80=9D =
known as the Internet Research Agency.According to the intelligence communi=
ty, the Russian government supported the email hacking of the Democratic Na=
tional Committee and the personal account of John D. Podesta, the Clinton c=
ampaign chairman, as well as the disclosure of Mrs. Clinton=E2=80=99s paid =
speeches. The committee emails, leaked just before the Democratic National =
Convention, helped increase the rancor between supporters of Mrs. Clinton a=
nd Senator Bernie Sanders.Finally, read Amanda Taub and Max Fisher's more s=
keptical take (https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/18/world/europe/russia-us-el=
ection.html), which argues that if Russia is the immediate cause of our wor=
ries, the larger and more existentially worrisome problem is homegrown poli=
tical polarization:

=C2=A0=E2=80=9CPartisanship can even alter memory, implicit evaluation, and=
 even perceptual judgment,=E2=80=9D the political scientists Jay J. Van Bav=
el and Andrea Pereira wrote in a recent paper. =E2=80=9CThe human attractio=
n to fake and untrustworthy news=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a danger cited by polit=
ical scientists far more frequently than orchestrated meddling =E2=80=94 =
=E2=80=9Cposes a serious problem for healthy democratic functioning.=E2=80=
=9DIt has infected the American political system, weakening the body politi=
c and leaving it vulnerable to manipulation. Russian misinformation seems t=
o have exacerbated the symptoms, but laced throughout the indictment are re=
minders that the underlying disease, arguably far more damaging, is all Ame=
rican-made.Ultimately, Russia's campaign succeeded in sowing discord and re=
ducing trust in American institutions. The extent to which it led directly =
to President Donald Trump's election is impossible to say. For our purposes=
 it's enough to know that social media was the interface through which Russ=
ia sought to unmake our democracy.

